### CSS Margin

**Margin** creates space **outside** the border.

---

### Individual Sides

```css
margin-top: 10px;
margin-right: 20px;
margin-bottom: 10px;
margin-left: 20px;
```

---

### Shorthand (1-4 Values)

```css
/* All sides */
margin: 20px;

/* Vertical | Horizontal */
margin: 10px 20px;

/* Top | Horizontal | Bottom */
margin: 10px 15px 20px;

/* Top | Right | Bottom | Left */
margin: 10px 15px 20px 25px;
```

---

### Margin Auto (Centering)

```css
.block {
  width: 300px;
  margin: 0 auto;  /* Horizontally center block */
}
```

`auto` takes available space equally on both sides.

---

### Negative Margins

```css
.box {
  margin-top: -20px;  /* Pulls element up */
  margin-left: -10px; /* Pulls element left */
}
```

Useful for overlapping elements or aligning.

---

### Margin Collapsing

**Vertical margins** of adjacent elements collapse (combine) into one:

```html
<div style="margin-bottom: 30px;">Box A</div>
<div style="margin-top: 20px;">Box B</div>
<!-- Gap = 30px (the larger value wins) -->
```

**Rules:**
- Only vertical margins collapse (top and bottom)
- Horizontal margins never collapse
- The larger margin wins
- Margins of floated/positioned elements don't collapse

---

### Margin Values

```css
/* Positive values */
margin: 10px;
margin: 1rem;
margin: 5%;     /* Percentage of parent WIDTH */

/* Auto for centering */
margin: 0 auto;

/* Negative for overlap */
margin-top: -10px;
```

---

> **Best Practice:** Use `margin` for space **between** elements. Use `padding` for space **inside** elements.
